  "doc_id": "42388",
  "text": "The reduced efficacy of viral transduction of NK cells compared to T cells may in part be related to the innate properties that characterize NK cells. Innate immune receptors, such as pattern recognition receptors that recognize foreign genomic material, are likely involved in triggering apoptosis of NK cells following viral transduction [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Although retroviral transduction of NK cells has been reported to not alter the function, phenotype, and proliferative capacity of NK cells [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , their viability following retroviral transduction has rarely been reported. A significant deleterious impact on the viability of primary NK cells undergoing retroviral transduction may preclude utilizing this approach in a clinical setting. Further, retroviral transduction also requires active cell division, impeding the use of this method with primary non-activated NK cells. This limitation is less important when retroviral transduction is utilized with NK cell lines such as NK-92 that have continuous and unlimited proliferation capacity. However, as discussed later in this review, it is important to note that this NK cell line does have phenotypic and function differences from primary human NK cells, which may have therapeutic implications for clinical therapy.",
